ions of employment. However, agricultural workers must still be given a <a href=\"/employment-contracts-and-conditions/written-statement-of-employment-particulars\" title=\"Written statement of employment particulars\">written statement of employment particulars</a> by their employer.</p>\n\n<h2>Trainees</h2>\n\n<p>Trainees have different rights, eg they don&rsquo;t get paid holidays.</p>\n\n<h2>Help and advice</h2>\n\n<p>The following document has more detailed guidance on agricultural workers&rsquo; rights. </p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://archive.defra.gov.uk/foodfarm/farmmanage/working/agwages/documents/awo-guidance11.pdf\" title=\"Download Agricultural Wages in England and Wales (PDF, 200KB\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Agricultural wages in England and Wales’ (PDF, 200KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You can phone the Pay and Work Rights Helpline for advice, or use their <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://payandworkrights.direct.gov.uk/\" title=\"Pay and Work Rights enquiry form\">online enquiry form.</a></p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Pay and Work Rights Helpline</strong>  </p>\n\n<p>Telephone: 0800 917 2368<br />\nTextphone: 0800 121 4042<br />\nMonday to Friday, 8am to 8pm <br />\nSaturday, 9am to 1pm</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Complaints about employers can be made on the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://payandworkrights.direct.gov.uk/complaints/\" title=\"Pay and Work Rights complaints form\">Pay and Work Rights complaints form.</a></p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/agricultural-workers-rights/what-counts-as-an-agricultural-worker","slug":"what-counts-as-an-agricultural-worker","order":2,"title":"What counts as an agricultural worker","body":"<p>An agricultural worker is someone who works in:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>farming and rearing animals</li>\n  <li>growing produce including non-edible crops like bulbs, plants and flowers</li>\n  <li>forestry, market gardens and nurseries</li>\n  <li>maintaining meadow or pasture land, woodlands and reed beds</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This list doesn&rsquo;t include everything. If you&rsquo;re not sure if a job counts as work in agriculture, call the Pay and Work Rights Helpline.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Pay and Work Rights Helpline</strong>  </p>\n\n<p>Telephone: 0800 917 2368<br />\nTextphone: 0800 121 4042<br />\nMonday to Friday, 8am to 8pm <br />\nSaturday, 9am to 1pm</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/agricultural-workers-rights/pay-and-overtime","slug":"pay-and-overtime","order":3,"title":"Pay and overtime","body":"<p>Agricultural workers must be paid at least the Agricultural Minimum Wage, or the <a href=\"/national-minimum-wage-rates\" title=\"National Minimum Wage rates\">National Minimum Wage</a> if that is higher. The Agricultural Minimum Wage depends on the worker&rsquo;s job <a href=\"/agricultural-workers-rights/grades-and-categories\" title=\"Grades and categories\">grade and category.</a></p>\n\n<h3>Trainees</h3>\n<p>A trainee doesn&rsquo;t have to be paid for:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the hours they&rsquo;re being trained</li>\n  <li>holidays</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>They should be paid for any work done as part of a separate contract.</p>\n\n<h2>Training courses</h2>\n<p>If an employed worker is on a training course, they should be paid at least their normal wage - including for the time spent travelling to and from the training.</p>\n\n<h2>Pay for grades 1 to 6</h2>\n<p>If a worker&rsquo;s contract says they should work 39 hours a week (not including overtime) they must be paid the weekly rate, otherwise they must be paid the hourly rate.</p>\n\n<table>\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th>&nbsp;</th>\n      <th>Weekly pay</th>\n      <th>Hourly pay</th>\n      <th>Hourly overtime</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 1 (compulsory school age)</td>\n      <td>n/a</td>\n      <td>£3.05</td>\n      <td>£4.58</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 1 (above compulsory school age)</td>\n      <td>£237.90</td>\n      <td>£6.10</td>\n      <td>£9.15</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 2</td>\n      <td>£264.03</td>\n      <td>£6.77</td>\n      <td>£10.16</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 3</td>\n      <td>£290.55</td>\n      <td>£7.45</td>\n      <td>£11.18</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 4</td>\n      <td>£311.61</td>\n      <td>£7.99</td>\n      <td>£11.99</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 5</td>\n      <td>£329.94</td>\n      <td>£8.46</td>\n      <td>£12.69</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 6</td>\n      <td>£356.46</td>\n      <td>£9.14</td>\n      <td>£13.71</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h2>Full-time and part-time flexible workers</h2>\n<p>Flexible workers must be paid at least the weekly rate if they are full-time, or at least the hourly rate if they are part-time.</p>\n\n<table>\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th>Grade of worker</th>\n      <th>Days per week</th>\n      <th>Hourly pay</th>\n      <th>Weekly pay</th>\n      <th>Hourly overtime</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 1</td>\n      <td>4 to 5</td>\n      <td>£6.41</td>\n      <td>£249.99</td>\n      <td>£9.15</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>&nbsp;</td>\n      <td>6</td>\n      <td>£6.53</td>\n      <td>£254.67</td>\n      <td>£9.15</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 2</td>\n      <td>4 to 5</td>\n      <td>£7.11</td>\n      <td>£277.29</td>\n      <td>£10.16</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>&nbsp;</td>\n      <td>6</td>\n      <td>£7.24</td>\n      <td>£282.36</td>\n      <td>£10.16</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 3</td>\n      <td>4 to 5</td>\n      <td>£7.82</td>\n      <td>£304.98</td>\n      <td>£11.18</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>&nbsp;</td>\n      <td>6</td>\n      <td>£7.97</td>\n      <td>£310.83</td>\n      <td>£11.18</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Grade 4</td>\n      <td>4 to 5</td>\n      <td>£8.39</td>\n      <td>£327.21</td>\n      <td>£11.99</td>\n    </tr>\n   