s if they&rsquo;ve been recommended by a doctor or midwife.</p>\n\n<p>Employers can&rsquo;t change a pregnant employee&rsquo;s contract terms and conditions without agreement - if they do they are in breach of contract.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>It’s illegal for employers to refuse to give pregnant employees time off for antenatal care or refuse to pay their normal rate for this time off, but fathers don’t have a legal right to time off to accompany their partners.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Pregnancy-related illnesses</h2>\n<p>If the employee is off work for a pregnancy-related illness in the 4 weeks before the baby is due, maternity leave and Statutory Maternity Pay will start automatically - it doesn&rsquo;t matter what has been previously agreed.</p>\n\n<h2>Compulsory maternity leave</h2>\n<p>If the employee isn&rsquo;t taking Statutory Maternity Leave, they must take 2 weeks off after the baby is born - or 4 weeks if they work in a factory.</p>\n\n<h2>Telling the employer about the pregnancy</h2>\n\n<p>Employees must tell their employer about the pregnancy at least 15 weeks before the beginning of the week the baby is due. </p>\n\n<p>If this isn&rsquo;t possible - eg because they didn&rsquo;t know they were pregnant - the employer must be told as soon as possible. </p>\n\n<p>Employees must also tell the employer when they want to start their <a href=\"/maternity-leave\" title=\"Statutory Maternity Leave\">Statutory Maternity Leave</a> and <a href=\"/statutory-maternity-pay\" title=\"Statutory Maternity Pay\">Pay</a>. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Employees can’t take time off for antenatal appointments until they’ve told the employer about the pregnancy.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Health and safety for pregnant employees</h2>\n\n<p>When the employee tells their employer they&rsquo;re pregnant, they should be prevented from exposure to any risks to protect them and the baby. </p>\n\n<p>Risks could be caused by:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>heavy lifting or carrying</li>\n  <li>standing or sitting for long periods without adequate breaks</li>\n  <li>exposure to toxic substances</li>\n  <li>long working hours</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If the employer can&rsquo;t remove any risks (eg by offering suitable alternative work) they should <a href=\"/expenses-and-benefits-medical-suspension-payments\" title=\"suspension from work for medical reasons\">suspend the employee on full pay</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Pregnant employees who think they&rsquo;re at risk but their employer disagrees should talk to their health and safety or trade union representative. If your employer still refuses to do anything, talk to your doctor or contact the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hse.gov.uk/contact/index.htm\" title=\"Contact the Health and Safety Executive\">Health and Safety Executive.</a></p>\n\n","alternative_title":""},"tags":[{"title":"Your rights at work and trade unions","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working%2Frights-trade-unions.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes health and safety, accidents at work and joining a trade union","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=working%2Frights-trade-unions","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/working/rights-trade-unions"},"parent":{"title":"Working, jobs and pensions","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes holidays and finding a job","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=working","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/working"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Trade unions and workers rights","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/employing-people%2Ftrade-unions.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes industrial action and recognising trade unions","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.js