esting time off</h2>\n\n<p>Employees should follow their organisation&rsquo;s rules to request time off. If there aren&rsquo;t any they can write to them saying it&rsquo;s a request &lsquo;under Section 63D of the Employment Rights Act 1996’ with the following details:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the date</li>\n  <li>the subject matter of the study or training</li>\n  <li>where and when it would take place</li>\n  <li>who will be providing the training</li>\n  <li>the name of the qualification you could get (if any)</li>\n  <li>why you think this study or training will help make you do your job better and help your employer&rsquo;s business</li>\n  <li>if you&rsquo;ve made a request before and when</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If all this information is not included an employer doesn&rsquo;t have to consider your request.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can normally only make 1 request every year.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>The employer&rsquo;s decision</h2>\n\n<p>The employer must either agree to the request or hold a meeting with the employee to discuss it within 28 days of getting the request. This might be longer if the person who deals with these requests is off when the request is sent in.</p>\n\n<p>If the employer decides to hold a meeting about it they must make a decision within 14 days of it, unless the employee agrees in writing to extend this time. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The employer can only turn down a request if they have a good business reason.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Appealing a decision</h2>\n\n<p>Employees have the right to appeal if their employer refuses a request to take time off for training or study.</p>\n\n<p>This must be made within 14 days of their employer&rsquo;s decision.</p>\n\n<p>The appeal must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>be in writing</li>\n  <li>be dated</li>\n  <li>set out why they’re appealing (the grounds for the appeal)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>The appeal meeting</h3>\n\n<p>The employer has to arrange a meeting with the employee to discuss the appeal within 14 days of getting the appeal.</p>\n\n<p>After the meeting, the employer must give their decision in writing within 14 days.</p>\n\n<h2>If the problem isn’t resolved</h2>\n\n<p>If an employee isn’t satisfied with the result of an appeal they can phone Acas (Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service) for help and advice or <a href=\"/raise-grievance-at-work\" title=\"raise a grievance\">raise a grievance</a>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Acas</strong><br />\n08457 47 47 47</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If this doesn’t work the employee could go to an <a href=\"/employment-tribunals\" title=\"employment tribunal\">employment tribunal</a> if the employer:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>didn’t follow the procedure properly</li>\n  <li>refused the request based on the wrong facts</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Employment tribunal claims must be made within 3 months of an appeal decision.</p>\n","alternative_title":"Training and study at work: an employee's legal right to request Time to Train"},"tags":[{"title":"Holidays, time off, sick leave, maternity and paternity leave","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working%2Ftime-off.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes career breaks and the holiday entitlement calculator","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=working%2Ftime-off","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/working/time-off"},"parent":{"title":"Working, jobs and pensions","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes holidays and finding a job","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=working","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/working"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Statutory leave and time off","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/employing-people%2Ftime-off.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes maternity and patern