":[{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/your-rights-if-your-employer-is-insolvent/overview","slug":"overview","order":1,"title":"Overview","body":"<p>If your employer is &lsquo;insolvent&rsquo; this means it can&rsquo;t pay its debts. You have rights if this happens and can make a claim for any money you are owed.</p>\n\n<h2>Types of insolvency</h2>\n\n<p>If you work for a company that&rsquo;s insolvent, this means one of the following:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>administration - where your employer asks an &lsquo;administrator&rsquo; to come in to try to keep the company going</li>\n  <li>liquidation - when a company is closed and its assets are sold to pay the people it owes money to (creditors)</li>\n  <li>receivership - like liquidation but it&rsquo;s usually arranged by a single creditor that&rsquo;s lent money securely (eg a bank), and the assets are sold to pay just that creditor</li>\n  <li>voluntary arrangement with creditors</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If your employer&rsquo;s an individual, insolvency is called either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>bankruptcy (&lsquo;sequestration&rsquo; in Scotland)</li>\n  <li>voluntary arrangement with creditors (&lsquo;deed of trust&rsquo; in Scotland)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The person who deals with the insolvency is called the ‘insolvency practitioner’.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Your rights</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re owed money, you can claim for it through the insolvency practitioner.</p>\n\n<h3>If you&rsquo;re asked to keep working</h3>\n\n<p>The business might keep running if there&rsquo;s a chance it can be rescued or sold. If this happens, you might be asked to continue working. </p>\n\n<p>This doesn&rsquo;t affect your rights to redundancy pay if the business closes down later.</p>\n\n<p>If the business is <a href=\"/selling-your-business-your-responsibilities\" title=\"sold to someone else\">sold to someone else</a>, your employment rights are protected, including any pay that&rsquo;s owed to you. </p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/your-rights-if-your-employer-is-insolvent/claiming-money-owed-to-you","slug":"claiming-money-owed-to-you","order":2,"title":"Claiming money owed to you","body":"<p>The insolvency practitioner will send you claim forms. If this doesn&rsquo;t happen, you should write to them. If you&rsquo;re not sure who they are, you can contact Companies House to find out:</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Companies House</strong>  <br />\n<strong>Telephone:</strong> 0303 1234 500<br />\n<strong>Textphone:</strong> 029 2038 1245   </p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>What you can get</h2>\n\n<p>The money comes from the government&rsquo;s National Insurance Fund. It&rsquo;s not guaranteed that you&rsquo;ll get everything your employer owes to you but you can claim for:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>redundancy</li>\n  <li>wages - up to 8 weeks&rsquo; worth </li>\n  <li>holiday pay - up to 6 weeks&rsquo; worth</li>\n  <li>statutory notice pay - 1 week after 1 month&rsquo;s service, going up to 1 week per year of service (up to a maximum of 12 weeks)</li>\n  <li>unpaid pension contributions (your pensions administrator does this for you)</li>\n  <li>basic award for unfair dismissal</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Your statutory notice period (the minimum legal notice period your employer has to give you) is:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>a week&rsquo;s notice if you&rsquo;ve been employed for between a month and 2 years</li>\n  <li>2 weeks&rsquo; notice plus an extra week for each year you&rsquo;ve worked if you&rsquo;ve been employed for 2 years (this goes up to a maximum of 12 weeks)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can claim for statutory notice pay if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you&rsquo;ve worked your statutory notice period but not been paid by your employer</li>\n  <li>you were dismissed without notice</li>\n  <li>you don&rsquo;t work your full notice</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can only claim up to £430 a week for your wages.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you&rsquo;re sick or becoming a parent</h2>\n\n<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) will pay you:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Statutory Sick Pay</li>\n  <li>Statutory Maternity Pay</li>\n  <li>Statutory Paternity Pay</li>\n  <li>Statutory Adoption Pay</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If your employer’s insolvent and you’re having trouble getting these payments, call <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> on 0191 225 5221 for help.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Redundancy</h2>\n\n<p>You can claim Statutory Redundancy Pay if you&rsquo;re made redundant and if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you&rsquo;ve been continuously employed for 2 or more years</li>\n  <li>you apply in writing to your employer or an <a href=\"/employment-tribunals\" title=\"Employment Tribunal\">Employment Tribunal</a> within 6 months of your job ending</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You claim by filling out form RP1, which you can get by calling 0845 015 0010 and quoting URN 10/708.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>The Insolvency Service has a redundancy payments factsheet to help you.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.bis.gov.uk/assets/bispartners/insolvency/docs/forms/redundancy-payments/urn12-561-rp1-fact-sheet\" title=\"Download 'Redundancy payments factsheet' (PDF, 18KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Redundancy payments factsheet’ (PDF, 18KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/your-rights-if-your-employer-is-insolvent/where-to-get-help","slug":"where-to-get-help","order":3,"title":"Where to get help","body":"<p>For information about insolvency, call the Insolvency Service.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Insolvency Service</strong><br />\n0845 602 9848</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>For information about redundancy payments, call the redundancy payments helpline.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Redundancy payments helpline</strong><br />\n0330 331 0020</p>\n</div>\n\n<div clas